						               													<description>&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#158;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#185;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#136;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#149;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#169;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#173;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#188;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#189;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#170;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#134;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#163;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#162; (Follow-the-Suit Solitaire) was designed for the 2019 exhibition &amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#147;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#140;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#175;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#136;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#170;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#134;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#170;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#174;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#139; (Is this a trick-taking game?), for games that pushed the boundary of what could be considered both a game and a trick-taking game.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;It is a solitaire game where the player wins if they can run out of cards in their hand; if they do, the player also earns a score equal to the number of cards left in a deck.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game uses a standard 52-card deck, plus 1 joker.  Ten cards and randomly discarded, then the player draws 10 cards from a shuffled deck.  The player may then discard any number of cards, drawing 2 cards to replace each card discarded.  The player can choose any or no suit as trump.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;To play a trick, the top card from the deck is flipped up and the player then chooses a card from their hand to play.  The player must follow suit (or play the joker).  The highest card played of the trump suit wins; otherwise the highest card played of the led suit.  (The joker is the highest overall card.) If the player wins, the two cards from the trick are discarded; otherwise, the player takes the cards into their hand.  Regardless of who wins the trick, the deck leads the next trick.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
